CIM 2019 was my last marathon. My second attempt at a sub-3 and while I got closer, I missed my goal by 84 seconds. I spent the final 4-5 miles watching my goal slip away and convincing myself that my family wouldn’t care if I didn’t hit my goal, that this wasn’t a big deal, and that I’d get another shot.

Three years later, I still relive this race vividly in my mind knowing that I was very capable of hitting my goal, but I GAVE UP. I gave up on myself and minimized my dream in those final miles. I committed to this goal for hours, months, years, and I diminished it in the moment I needed to be my biggest hype person.

I had no idea this would be my last marathon for a very long time and just how much my life and running would change shortly after this.

For anyone racing this weekend, your goals are important. Shoot your shot. Don’t give up on yourself when it gets hard because it will. Get gritty and fight for it. You never know when you’ll get another chance.

Race with no regrets ❤️

Keep going ❤️

There’s countless moments where I want to give up. Training is so hard. Made harder because my kid isn’t sleeping well and it’s a busy time of year trying to wrap up business things and spend time with family. I’m dragging a bit and finding it challenging to show up in the spaces I want to, but I’m determined to keep this focus of showing up for myself.

How do I keep going?

I watch videos of myself on my first run back at 11 weeks postpartum 👆🏼. It was a painful (emotionally) run/walk where I was barely able to recognize my body, struggling in my new roll as mama, trying to regain control of something with my running… only to be pulled back from it for another 4-5 months. It reminds how hard I’ve worked to be where I am today:

To be able to run back-to-back days.

To run a 20 mile long run.

To complete a speed workout.

To continue to build a solid foundation for the training ahead.

To be proud of something that is just mine.

Never again will I take the process of training or a single run for granted. I hope you don’t either - even on the hardest days remember how much work you’ve put in to get here ❤️.

Hey, hi 👋🏼! Still here, just took some time off to recover from a very sore throat that hit me the day before Christmas Eve and gave me a reason to rest a bit more during my recovery week!

Got in 28 miles last week instead of the 40 I had planned, but taking two days completely off (and medicine, of course 🙏🏻) helped me get back to training today.

Getting sick during training is never fun, and it’s hard sometimes to figure out whether you should rest or not. Often resting helps you get back into training faster than running through it. I used to be the athlete who hated missing training bc I got sick and would get hung up on “making up” the missed mileage, but now, I embrace it when my body needs rest and move on from any missed mileage with no desire to make it up. I want my body to perform when I need it to (I.e. on race day!), so no need to push my limits right now.

5 more weeks to go!! I hope you all had a great holiday ❤️

2022 was all about prioritizing myself, and I’m so glad I went all in on it because I’ve set a solid foundation to continue stacking bricks on in 2023 ✨

Mental health - in addition to finally going to therapy, prioritizing all of the other things I did this year helped support my mental health tremendously ❤️

Motherhood - Q and I have such a short time together and I’ve focused on embracing the messiness and neediness of this phase of life bc he eventually won’t need me at all 🥹. It’s been hard to let go of things, but cuddles > anything else.

Setting boundaries - in my business, with my training, with social media, and partnerships. Saying “no” has allowed me to be more present and available for the things I say “yes” to.

Getting strong - I have never committed to strength training in this way before and I will forever stick with it. It’s a grind and I’d rather be running, but I’m here for the discomfort bc it’s helping me grow 🌱

Running - yes, I would’ve loved to have done more - more races, maybe get close to a PR, run a marathon (I even thought I’d be at CIM this past month) - but I’m grateful I’ve taken the slow and steady road. I may not be where I want to be, but I reaffirmed that I love the journey more than the destination and consistent training is bringing me JOY 💕

What did you prioritize in 2022 that you’re taking into 2023?

Of course, I’d make it through peak week of my first postpartum marathon buildup and then an injury would crop up. I’ve been dealing with some runner’s knee in the same knee I had bursitis early last year which has likely been caused by tight quads/calves and weak hip abductors and external rotators 🤕😞.

Becoming a mom has given me so much perspective that I needed for this exact scenario. Running was my everything prior to Q and so, not having it would crush me. Old me would’ve cried, felt sorry for myself, and kind of lost my mind a bit with all the work I’ve put in and the uncertainty of whether I can get this under control in time to run the marathon. I’ve never had to DNS a marathon before.

Not only is running not my everything anymore, but I have someone little watching everything I do. How do I want him to face challenges in his life? By doing everything he can to reach his goal. The obstacle is the way.

So, if you follow me on Strava, you’ll see I’ve been ElliptiGOing my little heart out to keep my fitness up while I do all the things I should’ve been doing but couldn’t seem to find the time for until it was too late: ART, stretching, proper warmups and cool downs, strengthening the parts of my body I didn’t even realize were weak.

As someone who’s never had an injury that’s kept me from running aside from pregnancy and childbirth, it is hard to not WISH for my old body back when things like this happen. My pre-baby body that I knew so well. But wishing for that is pointless. This is my body now and I have to respect it. If I can’t run, I’m just going to focus on what I CAN DO.

Growth happens on your hardest days 🌱

The peaks of our journeys are EASY. It’s easy to keep going and stay positive when things are clicking, and everything falls into place.

Everyone hits a valley at some point. Whether it’s because of injury, overtraining, or life, it SUCKS. The easiest thing to do is give up. To crawl into a hole and disappear. To focus on the what ifs or what you could’ve done differently. To not put in the work that needs to be done. The hardest thing to do is to pivot and look at this as an opportunity to keep working towards your goals in a different way. You can approach them by giving up OR with a mindset of curiosity to make yourself stronger for your next climb.

I went from training for a marathon to doing more PT work in the last week than I have in my whole life. Guess what? I had my first PAIN FREE run in over 3 weeks yesterday and I didn’t take a single step of that slow slog on the treadmill for granted.

This has been a reality check for me that I need to take better care of my body. While I thought I was in a position to tackle the marathon again, I clearly wasn’t quite ready, and my body let me know that. I’m grateful for the opportunity to get better for my next attempt at the distance (stay positive!).

If you’re in a valley right now, keep working. It will pay off ❤️

Next step on my journey back to running pain free – a running assessment!

Prior to my running assessment with @olyperformance earlier this week at the recommendation of my physical therapist, I’d never had my form or gait analyzed in such detail and with such incredible technology.

Injury is often when athletes will look at getting their running form assessed, but I wish I had done this years ago and before I got injured. There is SO MUCH to learn and change which = lots of untapped potential and progress to be made.

Things I learned about my form:

💥 I have a slight posterior lean when I walk, likely from pregnancy, and need to work on hinging forward at the hip more when I’m running.

💥 I have hip drop and a lot of compensation in my trunk to make up for the lack of strength and mobility in my hips which is causing poor hip hinge and less extension at my hip.

💥 My knee is taking up the strain of what my hips are unable to do which led to my injury.

💥 I’m a forefoot runner and my gait is actually in a good position already to continue my path towards healing my injury.

And the solution? Get more activation in my glute medius, more strength in my hips, more stability in my hips and core, more forward lean…

Basically, get strong AF and apply it to my running.

Running might be taking a back seat for a while, but it will definitely be improved when it’s back in front. Let’s GO 🔥

Closing out February feeling like I’ve made A LOT of progress since getting injured last month. My Strava and Garmin might disagree, but let’s not bother with that!

When you’re injured or feel like your training is stagnant, there is always this feeling that you have to do more or work harder. I know this is where my thoughts have gone the last few weeks. This is the time to reframe what progress is and recognizing that the work you’re putting in, even if it doesn’t feel like it at the moment, will yield progress in the long run.

I shared in my stories today that despite only running 10 miles last week, I dedicated the same amount of time to my training that I did during my peak week of marathon training in early January when I ran 49 miles. WOW 🤯. I’ve been hitting the strength and physical therapy routines hard so I can work out the kinks in my mechanics and get back to pain free running.

Aside from focusing on getting stronger these last 6-7 weeks, I took a look under the hood and got an @insidetracker test done to make sure I’m covering all my bases. I’ve certainly got some areas to improve (like my now high and at risk iron levels?!), but I was happy to see my cortisol has started to go down a little bit (yay!). Getting injured has been stressful, but I have no doubt that taking a step back from running the last few weeks and prioritizing more sleep, has allowed my cortisol to improve.
@insidetracker also has a new biomarker on their Ultimate plan – ApoB or Apolipoprotein B which is a direct indicator of healthy cholesterol transport and clearance. It’s a key marker in heart health and I was thrilled to see mine was optimized!

If you’d like to get an @insidetracker test done, check out the link in my profile!

After 3 years away from hard training and racing the distance that I love due to pregnancy, postpartum setbacks, and adjusting to life with a baby, you’d think that getting an injury at my first attempt back at the marathon would leave me wanting to walk away from it. It’s been a tough and slow comeback.

Maintaining a growth mindset has kept me motivated and working hard through all the rough patches. Here’s what I focus on to keep this mindset and you might find this helpful in your own running (or life!) if you’re experiencing an injury or setback:

✨ Be open and willing to change. Having a beginner’s mindset and being open to learning new methods helps when you have to get back to the most basic things to get to that next level. Whatever you were doing, wasn’t working and that’s why you’re here. Embrace it like a newbie would!

✨Be eager for feedback on how to improve without taking it personally. It’s tough not to get sensitive to critique but focus on those critiques as a learning opportunity to better yourself. I ask tons of questions during my PT sessions so I can get the most out of it. I want the feedback!

✨Trust the experts! Whether it’s your physical therapist, coach, registered dietician, etc., trust their experience and expertise rather than thinking you know it all. Having questions is good for the learning process here, so don’t be scared to ask those experts as much as you can.

✨Be able and willing to adjust and persevere in the face of challenges! View challenges as learning opportunities rather than obstacles and then work through them. Challenges will continue to come up as you work your way through a setback because progress is NEVER linear.

Let me know if this resonates with you!

Obstacles = Opportunity = Growth 🌱

Your motivation and dreams can really take a hit when you get injured, but it isn’t the end of the journey. It’s just a small detour. Having crawled my way back from childbirth in 2021 to get back to racing in 2022, I felt better prepared to tackle my current injuries and keep myself motivated through this process.

Here are my top 5 tips for anyone working through an injury:

1️⃣Let go of timelines – if you give yourself a timeline to be back running by XX date, then you’ll see it as a failure if you aren’t there. Set your mind and body up for success by letting go of any timelines.

2️⃣ Don’t sign up for races – like tip # 1, signing up for a race to motivate yourself through injury doesn’t work. Having to DNS a race because your body isn’t ready can feel like you’re failing and may demotivate you. Leave your calendar open until you’re cleared.

3️⃣ Focus on what you CAN do – it’s easy to get stuck on “I CAN’T run,” but it’s not very helpful. There are usually a lot of things you can do to maintain fitness and build strength while injured. Focus on what you can do and build a routine around it in the same way you did running.

4️⃣ Work with a professional (if you can) – find a physical therapist or sports doctor who is going to get you back to where you want to be: running. The right one can provide the help and support you need to progress safely and build the appropriate strength so you avoid the same or other injuries in the future. Navigating injury on your own is tough. Having a knowledgeable support team helps.

5️⃣ Stay positive – the most challenging thing to do when you’re feeling down and out, but your body follows your mind. If you believe you will get through this and be chasing your dreams and goals again at some point, your body will get there. Don’t discount how powerful our thoughts are and be sure to speak kindly to yourself.

What’s your reason or “why” behind your running?

When I first started running, it was because I was lost without a team sport to direct me after college (I played soccer for 20 years!), so I started running a few days on the treadmill to “stay in shape.”

After running my first marathon, it became about finding my potential and pushing myself. How high could I aim? How fast could I be? Could I BQ? Am I capable of a sub-3?

After becoming a mom, running has been my safe haven. A way to create space for myself to keep those big scary dreams alive even if they are dimly lit. I still have time goals, but my biggest reason for continuing to pursue them has been to show my kid that setting goals and going after them no matter the obstacles is important, that you can learn from failure, and that there is beauty in loving something that is just for you ❤️.

My top *mental* tips for race day - these are the tools that helped me run a 3:07 and 3:01 marathon 💥 

⚡️ Visualize - take time in the days leading up to your race to sit in a quiet place with your eyes closed and focus on seeing yourself hitting your goal and feeling the emotions after you achieve it (relief, joy, excitement, etc.). Imagine how you want to feel at mile 15 (strong, capable) or at mile 20 (ready to push and find that extra gear). Do this on the plane, in the porto potty, at the start line.

⚡️Speak it - say out loud what you will do. When I ran Eugene in 2018 after an extremely rocky training cycle, I kept saying, “I’m going to run a 3:05” or “I am capable of running 7:05 pace for 26.2 miles” in the days leading up to the race. It helped me believe and push out the doubts or fear of failing. I ended up running a 3:07 flat which was a huge PR. Even though it wasn’t my goal time, I convinced myself I was capable of something big that day by speaking it out loud.

⚡️Accept the pain - in order to excel at something, you have to accept that it is going to be hard, painful, and challenging at some point. Our body follows our mind, and our mind tells us to stop well before we need to. Not being able to overcome these thoughts and welcome the pain is the biggest reason why we quit!

⚡️Smile - a 2018 study showed that smiling lowers our perceived exertion and improves running economy! Smile when you’re in a rough patch and see if it helps you through (it helps Kipchoge!).

These tools should be practiced in training too. Have a tough workout coming up? Visualize yourself crushing those intervals. Tell yourself you can run those scary AF paces your coach plugged in. Accept that it’s going to challenge you and be hard. And smile when you nail it or when you’re in pain to bring yourself back to the joy that is running and the opportunity this sport gives you to push yourself!

The many emotions and thoughts on that first run back after 6+ weeks off 🫠😅

I am very out of shape, but oh so happy to be back and looking forward to the process of building fitness again.

Let’s do this 🙌🏼

#comebackseason #marathoner #imback #runnerslife

Fact: Returning to running after injury or an extended break is humbling. 35 minutes of running this past week and every one of them felt way harder than I expected. Rather than being filled with complete joy, many of those minutes were filled with anxiety and dread for the challenging process that’s ahead and the realization that I have so much work to do. And I LOVE RUNNING. Really, I do. But I’ve had to remind myself that I don’t love it because it’s easy. I love it because it challenges me.

Those first few weeks getting back into running are crucial and it’s so important to not give up on yourself. A few of the things I’ve been concentrating on to help me through this process:

It takes 8-12 weeks to build up a running base. Week one is obviously hard AF.

Consistency is the only way to get fit. Stick with it.

Embrace the challenge now. Eventually, easy runs will feel effortless, and you’ll be humbled by speed workouts – it’s all part of the process.

Who else is getting back into a running groove right now?? Here to commiserate 😅🙋🏻‍♀️!

#returntorunning #comebackseason #newrunner #runmotivation #runningvlog #runwithme

Your reminder that consistency is the 🔑 to results.

If you’re new or returning to running after a long break, it can take months before running starts to feel more comfortable. Even when it does start to feel “easier,” running will still be challenging and uncomfortable, but your tolerance for discomfort increases ➡️ this is progress!

🚫 DON’T QUIT! 🚫

If you’re coming back to running after a goal race, it will take time to get back to your previous base fitness level.

✅ STAY COMMITTED ✅

This is part of the process.

After 6 weeks off running and 7 weeks of low volume prior to that, I’ve got some work to do! I’m lowering my expectations for these first 8-12 weeks while I commit to the process of building back fitness.

Share this with someone who needs the reminder to keep going! ❤️

Learn from my mistakes! I certainly have.

As I prepare to embark on another marathon training cycle that hopefully ends with me on the start line healthy as can be, there are 3 big mistakes I made in my last attempt at marathon training that left me injured:

1️⃣ Not enough sleep. Tracking my sleep the last month has been an eye opener. I’m not sure how I made it as far as I did in training last winter, but I undoubtedly set my body up for failure and got injured because I wasn’t able to get enough recovery through sleep. Sleep is the easiest way to optimize recovery!

2️⃣ Lack of mobility work. I was doing the strength work (and clearly got stronger), but without the mobility piece coupled with a postpartum body that was still coming back together and learning to manage training load again, my body lacked full range of motion which affected my running form and efficiency and I got injured.

💡Mobility and flexibility are not the same thing. Mobility is the ability of a joint to move through full range of motion which requires strength, coordination, flexibility, and motor control, while flexibility is the ability of the muscles and soft tissue to lengthen. Make sure you include mobility in your training! Your body will thank you and you will be a stronger, more resilient athlete.

3️⃣ Thinking I was the same runner I was before. While I had a major life event with pregnancy, I also took a lot of time away from running, my priorities shifted, and I got older. I cannot manage the same amount of running volume I used too. I cannot run 6 days/week anymore. I cannot sacrifice strength, mobility, or sleep and expect my body to show up for me like it did before. I cannot run a 25 mile week because I got sick and had to skip my long run and follow that with a 50 mile week and not expect to hurt myself (which is what I did).

Running is such a learning process as our bodies constantly change and grow. Grateful to be finally listening to my body again instead of just gritting my way through it.

Sharing the 3 exercises that have been most helpful for my runner’s knee injury recovery. I do these weekly (some daily, as part of my pre run warm up) to continue building strength and keep this injury at bay.

My primary goal has been to strengthen my glute med and work on proper tracking of my knee over my toe in a single leg position, which all of these address.

1️⃣ Captain Morgan: you can start with pressing your knee against a wall with no movement and progress to a Pilates ball and eventually the larger exercise ball while squatting down. You can also add weight to progress this. Focus on keeping the hips level and pushing your knee into the ball (or wall) to engage the glute med on the standing leg. I use this move as part of my prerun warm up to fire up my glutes 🔥.

2️⃣ On the banded three way tap, I focus on engaging my big toe, pushing it into the ground, and trying not to curl up my other toes. Progressing this one next to have the standing leg up on the ball of my foot to strengthen my posterior tibialis 😅.

3️⃣ The three way taps off box were very challenging for me initially, especially on the front side, so start with no weight to ensure your knee is tracking correctly before progressing with weight. These ones wear out my glute med quickly, so I save them for the end!

Be sure to save for later and let me know if you try any of these exercises!

I’m sure you’ve heard the phrase “get comfortable with being uncomfortable” A LOT. What’s does that actually mean??

It means training your brain to know that you’ll survive when things get tough. Our brains are trying to protect us - when our exertion increases, it signals our brain that something is not right, our body is at an increased risk, and we should stop. That’s the overwhelming feeling you get when you want to quit in the middle of a tough interval or in a race.

🚨 The wonderful news is - you can train your brain to accept discomfort and work through it so you can get more out of yourself. Each time we push our body to discomfort, it trains our brain to accept a bit more discomfort.

How can you work on this in training?

Stop distracting yourself from being uncomfortable. Focus on it, sit with it, acknowledge it, accept it.

I stopped listening to music on my runs several years ago. It was initially for safety (I got assaulted on a run when I was listening to music and never heard him coming), but the benefit of doing speed workouts and long runs without music was HUGE for my mental endurance. I was more focused and able to hone my mental skills. I was able to talk myself out of quitting and acknowledge how hard and challenging the work was.

💡 If you’re used to running with distractions - podcasts, audiobooks, music - try running without it a few times/week and work your way up to doing a long run with zero distractions.

Mental training is 90% of endurance sports. Let’s start building that mental muscle 🧠💪🏼!

12 more days in the boot and then I get to relearn how to use my foot!

Stopping my run just over 4 weeks ago, asking my husband to come pick me up instead of running through it, and putting myself in a boot right away helped reduce my healing time from 8 weeks to 6. It feels good to know I did the right thing. But of course, I’m endlessly curious as to HOW this happened to me when I felt like I was already doing all the right things:

I fueled my body adequately.

I took a conservative approach to training, increasing weekly mileage by less than 10% and taking down weeks.

I strength trained.

Sometimes you do everything right, and you still get injured, but knowing why is most helpful to avoiding the same situation in the future.

My doc didn’t think my ferritin was low enough for long enough to cause this injury (a relief that this wasn’t caused by me ignoring my fatigue levels).

There’s only one thing I can attribute to this injury: changing my form.

If you’re injured like I was, you want to evaluate your form. My runner’s knee was a strength issue – poor core and glute strength along with other weaknesses in my kinetic chain caused my knee to fall out of alignment when running. When I evaluated my form prior to my broken toe, I wanted to work on more of a forward lean. I wanted my form to look more “pretty,” instead of staying focused on the strength I needed to build. I overcorrected myself.

The second and third metatarsal take the brunt of our weight when we land on our foot (2-3 times our bodyweight landing on those very tiny bones). In my effort to do a more forward lean, I was landing mostly on my forefoot instead of my midfoot. Doing this after taking 6 weeks off running was a lot for these bones to adjust to and they eventually couldn’t sustain the pressure even though my volume was low and I increased load safely.

I’m not here to dissuade anyone from changing their form. Improving form can lead to more efficient running and better performance. But changing your form is a big deal and something my body wasn’t quite ready for with the remaining weaknesses I needed to address first.

Feeling nervous and excited to be a beginner… again (soon).

Four days left in this boot and I catch myself worrying about starting over and how hard it will be. Thinking about how much I’ve lost the last six weeks and maybe the last year unable to string together healthy weeks or months of training.

But starting over also brings the opportunity to do things better. To address my weaknesses. To not make the same mistakes. To take better care of myself in pursuit of my goals.

In many ways this past year has felt like a wash. But has it been?

I’ve learned a lot about my body.

I’ve lost endurance, but I’ve gained strength in my weakest areas.

I’ve had way too many injuries and false starts, but they’ve reaffirmed that running is always there waiting.

Sometimes you have to reflect on your journey and remind yourself that you ARE CAPABLE of achieving what you want even if it means starting over. You’ve done this before… 😉

Almost go time ✨

Took a break on here bc I was searching for answers. It’s been 8 weeks since my stress fracture and I’m cleared to start a run/walk on Monday. I should be excited, but I’m not.

The last 10 months have been grueling for my mental health to not only not be able to run to my full capacity, but not knowing when or if I’ll ever feel my best again. Battling broken bones, two 6-week bouts of no running that brought minimal relief to my knee, working my ass off to get stronger just to lose running repeatedly.

Through all of this, my knee has never felt 100%. While wearing my boot this past month, the discomfort actually got worse. It is manageable, but I couldn’t imagine running 20+ miles with it let alone racing a marathon the way I want to. So, I finally got an MRI of my knee.

The MRI revealed plica syndrome and a small meniscus tear in addition to the tendinitis that I thought was the only source of my issues. After months of conservative treatment and with more understanding of what’s actually going on, I’ve decided to have surgery.

Plica syndrome is a fold in my membrane underneath my kneecap that causes my knee to catch and become inflamed. Running irritates it and will continue to irritate it until it’s fixed.

The meniscus tear is a bit trickier. My doctor won’t know the extent of the tear until he goes in and determines if it can be repaired (the best outcome) or needs to be removed (the worst-case scenario which would lead to continued cartilage loss, arthritis, and would ultimately limit my running). The tear is small and on the part of the meniscus that gets blood flow and can heal, which is a good sign already.

I’m nervous more than anything and also, somehow disappointed. As if there was a way I could’ve done more, but I know I worked as hard as I could to fix things myself.

I’m also hopeful that this will prolong my athletic career for many years. I’ve learned so much the last 10 months - mainly that you are your biggest advocate. Get the second opinion and keep pushing for answers.

Do these amounts surprise you ⁉️

Something I constantly work on with my athletes (and myself) is increasing fuel intake during their runs.

You may be saying to yourself, “I could never take in that much on a run.” But that is WHAT TRAINING IS FOR! You MUST train your gut just as you train your muscles and mind — over time.

If you’ve been in the rut of: had some GI distress bc of gels/fuel -> won’t fuel again -> body never gets used to fueling on the run -> constantly bonking on runs and in races — STOP that cycle 🛑!

Start small. If you’re getting in a 25g/carb gel per hour now, aim to start your fueling a bit earlier on your next run and continue to work on decreasing the time between taking your gels (or chews or waffles or dates or hydration/carb mix — so much to choose from!) gradually until you get to a tolerable amount that is within recommended range.

If you’re just starting out with intra run fueling, it will take a longer time to increase these amounts as your gut becomes accustomed to taking in fuel during activity.

‼️REMEMBER: it’s better to have a training run suck as your body becomes accustomed to fueling or to help you figure out that a type of fuel doesn’t work for you than to experience that during a race OR bonk during your race because you never figured out how to fuel.

So, CARB UP ⬆️ (and don’t forget about hydration too!).

If you want to improve your running this year (and beyond), here are 6 things to focus on:

1. Consistency - good things take time and the only way to see results is by sticking with it through the highs and lows.

2. Commitment/Discipline - make training a non-negotiable. Of course, it doesn’t have to be perfect (training rarely is), but be disciplined with your choices to support your training so you can reach those goals.

3. Belief in yourself - you must be your own biggest fan bc no one will care about your goals more than you. When those doubtful thoughts creep in, that unwavering belief in yourself needs to be there to fight.

4. Quality sleep - sleep is essential for recovery. Create good habits around sleep so you can get the most out of yourself. One thing I’m working on this year is no screen time 30 mins before bed (so hard).

5. Fueling - adequate fueling before, during, after runs and on rest days ensures you have enough energy to tackle workouts, perform at your best, and helps you avoid injuries.

6. Stop comparing - everyone’s journey is different. Comparing often gets us into trouble — mentally and physically. Focusing on yourself, the season you’re in, and running at your current fitness level will keep you healthy, enjoying the process, and making progress.

While PRs are great, running is about so much more than that. Having goals that support your training and allow you to focus on the process and not just the results helps maintain longevity in our sport.

If you need some non-time related goal ideas, I’ve got plenty for you:

💪🏼 Strength train 2x per week: this habit will make you a stronger and more resilient runner which means you’ll avoid injury and setbacks.

🆕 Run a new distance: been marathoning for years straight? Tackle the 5k, or take to the trails. Variety helps us overcome plateaus and you may surprise yourself with how much you enjoy it!

🏃🏻‍♀️Join a run club or find a running buddy: I love solo runs, but running with friends is very fun and makes miles fly by. You might meet the training partner or friend you’ve been searching for at a local run club!

🍎 Improve intra-run fueling: we all need to work on this, no? More fuel = a faster, more efficient engine! If you’ve struggled to take in enough fuel during your runs, have a goal to gradually increase your intake.

🫣 Tackle your weakest area: avoid hills or doing the same speed workout every week? Doing the things you’re not good at or enjoy less is where you get uncomfortable and start to see growth.

🏁 Improve race execution: struggle with starting too fast and burning out? Implement progression runs or fast finish runs into your training. Race a little more so you get better at controlling yourself on race day.

LESSONS LEARNED👇🏼

After a year of injuries, searching for answers, and ending in surgery, I learned a lot from this process and hope this helps anyone who’s struggled with injuries or constant setbacks.

1️⃣ The importance of seeking multiple opinions: My initial self-diagnosis of runner’s knee and taking myself to physical therapy in January 2023 were steps in the right direction, but after taking 6 weeks off running with my broken toe and the pain coming back, I should’ve sought another opinion and gotten imaging done.

2️⃣ Patience + persistence: Dealing with multiple injuries and setbacks requires both patience and persistence. I was committed to addressing the issues at hand, including a conservative marathon buildup and ongoing physical therapy. Despite the challenges, I’ve continued to pursue a solution for my injuries and work towards recovery. This entire experience has brought me back to my main goal with running - whether I ever hit a PR again, I want to be able to run forever. Find your why and persist.

3️⃣ You are your biggest advocate: You are the one who knows your body best. For months, I thought I wasn’t working hard enough in PT even though I spent almost the same amount of time on strength and PT that I did running 50 miles per week. I was working hard, but it wasn’t working. I thought I was good at advocating for myself, but wish I had asked more questions earlier about who I should see or what my options were if my pain wasn’t going away. Seeing an orthopedic doctor and advocating for advanced imaging allowed for a clearer understanding of the root of my issue.

Many times I’ve told myself, “how could I have known what to do?” While it’s not my job to KNOW, it’s my job to advocate, push, and persist until I have answers for myself. If something isn’t sitting right, keep searching!
